    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras face a challenging slate today, exacerbated by the confirmed rainouts of **Yordan Alvarez**, **Trea Turner**, and **Kyle Schwarber**. With these high-impact bats unavailable, we lean heavily into **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (77.34) and **Junior Caminero** (76.33) as our primary offensive drivers. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** is our top play today; while he occupies the 8-hole, he faces a soft matchup against Waldron (xERA 7.83), where his elite sprint speed and a +14% dynamic platoon boost make him a high-upside asset in a 5x5 format where steals are at a premium. **Junior Caminero** remains a locked-in core piece, capitalizing on his prime No. 2 spot against Williams to generate strong run-scoring opportunities.\n\nThe middle of our lineup features solid production from **Hyeseong Kim** (62.33) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (61.55). **Hyeseong Kim** benefits from favorable wind conditions (+5%) that boost his power profile, offsetting the minor penalty of batting seventh. Meanwhile, **Kazuma Okamoto** continues to be a reliable anchor at 1B, showing resilience against Bello despite the R/R platoon disadvantage. **Chase Meidroth** (60.91) also edges into our \"Strong\" tier; his position at the top of the lineup against Kikuchi provides the volume required to mitigate his limited power ceiling.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Dillon Dingler** (33.08), who failed to clear the Zebras\u2019 40.0 floor. While he offers some catching depth, the combination of Ritchie\u2019s elite SP skill (2.08 xERA) and a significant -15% penalty due to platoon dynamics made him an easy exclusion in favor of **Gary Sanchez**, whose power profile against Rodriguez keeps him slightly above the threshold. We are monitoring **Colt Keith** (47.28) closely; he is an active start, but his score is suppressed significantly by the matchup against Ritchie, leaving little room for error if he fails to capitalize on his top-third lineup placement.",
